50|$|Historic Angostura {{gave its}} name to the Congress of Angostura, to the <b>Angostura</b> <b>tree,</b> and to Angostura bitters. Modern Ciudad Bolívar has a well-preserved {{historic}} center; a cathedral and other original colonial buildings surround the Plaza Bolívar.|$|E
50|$|Over {{the course}} of time, Angostura bitters and Dr. Siegert's company alone became {{purveyor}} to the King of Prussia, Spain, and King George V. Today, angostura bitters are also produced by various other vendors, some of which add the bark of the <b>angostura</b> <b>tree</b> (Angostura trifoliata). Angostura bitters are a key ingredient in many cocktails, for example in pink gin and the Manhattan. Angostura brand bitters do not contain any angostura bark. There are several other companies that make bitters containing this bark, notably Fee Brothers and Riemerschmid.|$|E

